{"id":"2205.13556","submitter":"Francesco Di Filippo","authors":"Ra\\'ul Carballo-Rubio, Francesco Di Filippo, Stefano Liberati,\n  Costantino Pacilio, Matt Visser","title":"Regular black holes without mass inflation instability","comments":"16 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/JHEP09(2022)118","report-no":"YITP-22-53","categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Generic models of regular black holes have separate outer and inner horizons,\nboth with nonzero surface gravity. It has been shown that a nonzero inner\nhorizon surface gravity results in exponential instability at the inner horizon\ncontrolled by this parameter. This phenomenon takes the name of \"mass inflation\ninstability\", and its presence has put in question the physical viability of\nregular black holes as alternatives to their (singular) general relativity\ncounterparts. In this paper, we show that it is possible to make the inner\nhorizon surface gravity vanish, while maintaining the separation between\nhorizons, and a non-zero outer horizon surface gravity. We construct specific\ngeometries satisfying these requirements, and analyze their behavior under\ndifferent kinds of perturbations, showing that the exponential growth\ncharacteristic of mass inflation instability is not present for these\ngeometries. These \"inner-extremal\" regular black holes are thereby better\nbehaved than singular black holes and generic regular black holes, thus\nproviding a well-motivated alternative of interest for fundamental and\nphenomenological studies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 26 May 2022 18:00:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-28"}
